  "text": "; see [CITATION_1] ). The T-, C-, Y-and R-type oil droplets were assumed to be filled with no carotenoid, galloxanthin, zeaxanthin and astaxanthin, respectively; in the latter three cases, the density of the carotenoids was varied. The cone spectral sensitivities were calculated with S(l) \u00bc T(l)(1 2 exp[2dk max P(l)]), where T(l) \u00bc 1 2 A(l) is the oil droplet transmittance, and P(l) is the normalized visual pigment absorption spectrum, calculated with a rhodopsin template [CITATION_2] using average, rounded peak wavelength values: l max \u00bc 390, 450, 505 and 565 nm, respectively [CITATION_3] . Applying the same procedure, we also calculated the spectral sensitivities of the cone photoreceptor set of the blue tit, Cyanistes caeruleus (previously Parus caeruleus), using the visual pigment peak wavelengths l max \u00bc 372, 449, 502 and 563 nm, whereas the transmittance of the transparent oil droplet was T(l) ",
